{\page #{\footnote # SPC700}}
{\keepn
{\fs24\cf1\b SNESAmp v3.1\par}
{Super NES® APU emulator plug-in for Winamp\par}}
{\par
The APU in the SNES was a separate module made from a Sony SPC700 and DSP, and 64K of RAM.  The
 SPC700 was an 8-bit processor that ran at 1.024MHz.  Programs were written for the SPC700 to play
 music with the DSP.\par\par
The DSP was an eight voice wavetable synthesiser.  Each voice has its own left and right volume
 control, envelope, pitch, and instrument settings, as well as the ability to use effects such as
 echo, pitch modulation, and noise generation.  The main output of the DSP was 16-bit 32kHz stereo.\par\par
With emulators, it is now possible to freeze the state of the APU at any moment and dump the memory
 and registers to a file.  These files (SPC's) can be loaded by stand-alone APU emulators (like
 SNESAmp) and resume playing.
}


